        <h3 class="bad-subtitle">IN THE BEGINNING, HOW WE STARTED, OUR AIMS AND GOALS</h3>
        <p>Black Bandcamp is a community based platform and database, hosting over 2,800 international Black owned record labels, artists, producers and bands.</p>
        <p>This crowed-sourced database provides an easy way to sort through, filter and thus support Black artists worldwide via their Bandcamp profiles.</p>
        <p>The database is a continuous work-in-progress administered by a group of volunteers, committed to ensuring as many Black artists are admitted onto the website. (Disclaimer: We are not affiliated with Bandcamp).</p>
        <p>Starting as a spreadsheet by a group of likeminded music enthusiasts, Black Bandcamp was primarily formed to further leverage Black artists, labels and producers, in an accessible database format which could be added to and circulated.</p>
        <p>The two key socio-political factors that contributed to the initial creation of Black Bandcamp, were the Black Lives Matter movement and the global pandemic.</p>
        <p>Created on 4th June 2020, Black Bandcamp was formed as part of the global uprise in support of Black Lives Matter. With the murder of George Floyd and other Black folk globally, Black Bandcamp was created as a response to the structural mistreatment of Black folk in the (underground) electronic industry. In addition to this, the whitewashing and eurocentrism of the (underground) electronic industry, the culture in which this music is rooted - Black culture - had not been accredited to this marginalised community.</p>
        <p>The realisation of how unbalanced and corrupt the music industry is, was a thought heightened during the global pandemic, where a ‘reset’ and reflection had begun - with global inequalities being highlighted and actioned against. Whilst it should not have taken a global pandemic for action to be taken, the circumstances meant more momentum could be built; this momentum was key to the project growing to this point, becoming a widely embraced resource within the community.</p>
        <p>In addition to the Black Lives Matter movement and the global pandemic, Bandcamp Fridays were another factor spurring the creation of Black Bandcamp.</p>
        <p>With Bandcamp waiving their fees every first Friday of the month throughout 2020, this was a prime opportunity for people to directly support Black artists in a monetary sense. As we had been actively engaging with and utilising Bandcamp days to already directly support artists - at the time - it was the only available and functioning mechanism for supporting artists. The exposure of highly exploitative digital and streaming music platforms became ever more apparent, which further spurred us to create Black Bandcamp.</p>
        <p>By having such a wealth of Black artists on a centralised platform, it enables the Black voice to shine as a collective. By creating, maintaining, and publicising the database, the community surrounding Black Bandcamp is able to try and sidestep the structural inequity present in the music industry.</p>
