        <h3 class="bad-subtitle">SELF DEFINITION.</h3>
        <p>With the definition and term ‘Black’ being relative to each individual’s geographical location, genetic make up and societal conceptualisation, we have a team who screen each and every submission to ensure that the space is preserved for Black artists. It’s important to note, we do not want to define what is Black for others, and encourage self-definition. Ask Raag to add their process of screening.</p>
        <p>This educational process has taught us the many different ways in which Black people identify with their race from each and every corner of the world. For those from the African continent, the term Black is not commonly used as a way of describing oneself. Being the majority race on the continent means that identifying oneself as Black is not necessary.</p>
        <p>On the African continent, racial labels do not have weight as there is a general and common understanding that everyone is the same - people celebrate their ethnicity and nationalities. What is key to note however, is that the matter of race still plays a part in our identity as a result of colonisation, as pre colonial systems work to undermine African’s.</p>
        <p>To ensure that we represent a full range of Black voices and protect and uplift those from further marginalised groups, we actively engage with a broad range of groups from within the Black global community. We seek out those that are less visible in the dance music industry, and we are consistent in airing our intentions and in reaching out to these communities. give a voice and platform to Black artists from alternative genres and backgrounds (not exclusively electronic music).</p>
        <p>We are committed to representing and collaborating with artists outside of the European and North American dance music sphere, by utilising our networks and ties from the African, Australiasian and South American continents. When possible we aim to collaborate with like minded organizations and institutions working to uplift marginalised creatives, for example: queer communities, the differently abled, the underprivileged; giving everyone in the Black underground music community a voice. One of the foundations we have for this action is having a diverse internal and core team and correspondents from varying parts of the world uniting under the same cause.</p>
        
