        <h3 class="bad-subtitle">THE FUTURE.</h3>
        <p>We hope to leverage the platform that has been created to further service the community, and to strive towards the goals outlined above. Black Bandcamp was created in the midst of the COVID-19 pandemic; to this end, the project so far has remained focused on the online space. In the future we hope to reach out to the physical space, with talks, parties and other celebratory events. Maintaining a presence in the physical sense is beneficial to the furthering of Black liberation, Black ownership and respect within the industry. Creating spaces where Black people can be comfortable, safe and enjoying themselves is a goal in its own right, but it also inspires newer generations of Black folk; serves to form networks; educates all folk on the origins of the music they so love.</p>
        <p>In the online space, we plan to continue to maintain, expand and promote the database, and work to ensure that those on it have a platform upon which they can showcase their art. To this end, the previews, editorial content, and special features will continue to be produced by our team, to highlight sections and individuals within the Black community.</p>
        <p>As Black Bandcamp grows and develops, we hope to further decentralise the overall structure, framework and basis of the community and platform, working towards a flatter set-up, free from gate-keepers.</p>
